{"PageNumber":1,"Angle":0,"RotatedAngle":0,"Height":2376,"Width":1836,"OriginHeight":0,"OriginWidth":0,"Elements":[{"Index":0,"Type":"title","Text":"#  1.3 Builder Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":212,"Y":250},"LeftTop":{"X":212,"Y":214},"RightBottom":{"X":478,"Y":250},"RightTop":{"X":478,"Y":214}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":1,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Builder Method is a creational design pattern, it provides an interface for constructing an object and then have concrete builder classes that implement this interface to create specific","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":345},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":255},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":345},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":255}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":2,"Type":"title","Text":"##  1.4 Prototype Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":212,"Y":431},"LeftTop":{"X":212,"Y":388},"RightBottom":{"X":505,"Y":431},"RightTop":{"X":505,"Y":388}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":3,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Prototype Method is a creational design pattern,pattern it provides to create new objects with the same structure and initial state as an existing object without explicitly specifying their class or construction details.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":559},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":431},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":559},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":431}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":4,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"1.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":206,"Y":647},"LeftTop":{"X":206,"Y":609},"RightBottom":{"X":250,"Y":647},"RightTop":{"X":250,"Y":609}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":5,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Singleton Method is a creational design pattern, it provides a class that has only one instance, and that instance provides a global point of access to it.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":785},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":694},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":785},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":694}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":6,"Type":"title","Text":"#  2. Structural Design Patterns in Java","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":870},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":827},"RightBottom":{"X":784,"Y":870},"RightTop":{"X":784,"Y":827}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":7,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Structural design patterns are a subset of design patterns in software development that focus on the composition of classes or objects to form larger, more complex structures. They help in organizing and managing relationships between objects to achieve greater flexibility, reusability, and maintainability in a software system.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1046},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":868},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1046},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":868}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":8,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Types of Structural Design Patterns in Java:","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1134},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1086},"RightBottom":{"X":803,"Y":1134},"RightTop":{"X":803,"Y":1086}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":9,"Type":"title","Text":"##  2.1 Adapter Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1174},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1134},"RightBottom":{"X":489,"Y":1174},"RightTop":{"X":489,"Y":1134}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":10,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Adapter Method is a structural design pattern, it allows you to make two incompatible interfaces work together by creating a bridge between them.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1262},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1174},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1262},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1174}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":11,"Type":"title","Text":"##  2.2 Bridge Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1350},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1307},"RightBottom":{"X":471,"Y":1350},"RightTop":{"X":471,"Y":1307}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":12,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Bridge Method is a structural design pattern, it is designed to separate an object's abstraction from its implementation so that the two can vary independently.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1440},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1350},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1440},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1350}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":13,"Type":"title","Text":"##  2.3 Composite Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1524},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1481},"RightBottom":{"X":522,"Y":1524},"RightTop":{"X":522,"Y":1481}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":14,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Composite Method is a structural design pattern, it's used to compose objects into tree structures to represent part-whole hierarchies. This pattern treats both individual objects and compositions of objects; it allows clients to work with complex structures of objects as if they were individual objects.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1657},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1526},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1657},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1526}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":15,"Type":"title","Text":"##  2.4 Decorator Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1740},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1702},"RightBottom":{"X":513,"Y":1740},"RightTop":{"X":513,"Y":1702}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":16,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"The Decorator Method is a structural design pattern, it allows to add behavior to individual objects, either statically or dynamically, without affecting the behavior of other objects from the same class.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1832},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1742},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1832},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1742}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":17,"Type":"title","Text":"##  2.5 Facade Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1913},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1875},"RightBottom":{"X":476,"Y":1913},"RightTop":{"X":476,"Y":1875}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":18,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Facade Method is a structural design pattern, it provides a simplified, higher-level interface to a set of interfaces in a subsystem, making it easier for clients to interact with that subsystem.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":2006},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1916},"RightBottom":{"X":1633,"Y":2006},"RightTop":{"X":1633,"Y":1916}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""}]}